                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d406">
                <head>No. 406.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Thomas</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Frelinghuysen</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Stockholm</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1884-05-03">
                            <hi rend="italic">May</hi> 3, 1884</date>. (Received May 21.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 65.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to my dispatch No. 29 on the subject of
                    direct steam communication between the United States and Sweden, I have the
                    honor to inform you that the Leipzig, the pioneer steamer of the first direct
                    steamship line between the two countries, sailed from Gothenburg, Sweden, direct
                    for New York, at 2 o’clock on the afternoon of May 1, having on board 228
                    emigrants, and 220 tons cargo.</p>
                <p>I have, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>W. W. THOMAS, <hi rend="smallcaps">Jr.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
